	<body>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+16" width="282" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0">
		<![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="11" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">
		<B>been entombed,  caliciviruses,  hundreds,  rising sea levels,  the Arctic,  climate change,  Greenland,  different methods,  ultraviolet light,  survived,  RNA,  remained unchanged,  PCR,  millions,  the flu virus,  protective clothing,  Antarctica,  the tobamovirus,  thousands,  the latest technology</B></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+16" width="282" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">Researchers have found a virus known as ToMV preserved in ice of up to [1] of years old. Despite being frozen for such a length of time, it is believed that the ToMV could still cause infections. For this reason, the team used [2] to avoid contamination while handling the ice. If other similar viruses exist in the ice, there is a fear that [3] may release them and result in epidemics. The discovery could also help answer questions concerning the evolution of viruses such as [4]. These viruses have puzzled scientists because they have [5] for so long. Future research is planned using [6] to study even older ice from [7].</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph height="0" width="282" y="+16" x="12"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="2"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph height="0" width="282" y="+16" x="12"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="2"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
